values:
Although I posted awhile back saying I decided to bring this up now that I can't rely on Branden to fill people in on the events surrounding me (since 1st: he became not my roommate 2nd: I moved to Davenport, IA and 3rd: he's not at USD anymore either) but then never really got around to doing anything with it. Really, I don't imagine that I'll remember to post much now either since classes just started again this past week and I have boards I in September.

For those who don't know, I'm in Davenport, IA attending Palmer College of Chiropractic and just finished my first year here. It sucked... a lot... but it should get better now that I'm away from most of the anatomy and physiology classes and finally into nifty stuff like instrumentation and my first trimester (out of 5) of radiology. Also, this tri is the first one where we actually start learning any techniques. Specifically, toggle recoil (aka Palmer upper cervical; hole in one; etc.). This, of course, being an upper cervical technique and thus will end up being different from the full spine techniques (such as Gonstead and Diversified) that I'll be learning later. Namely the differences are in the listing system (the system to determine misalignments and/or sublixations based on adjacent vertebra) and recoil being part of the technique instead of a hold due to differences in cervical anatomy compared to most of the spine. In addition to the required techniques here I'm thinking of also getting into some cranial work, SOT, and activator (I personally don't like activators, but I know some people greatly prefer it). Also, I think clinic abroad would be a pretty nifty experience later on when I can. Either to India or Fiji (Madagascar and Brazil are two other options out of a small list of them. I can't really remember the others). Finally, I also started self-study Japanese. Probably a bit foolish since I have no time to make progress and there's so much progress that really needs to be made for proficiency, but for now I'm trying. All I really have though are the entire Katakana and Hiragana systems, but no Kanji and as far as vocabulary goes I just have the days of the week, months of the year, 1-10, the four directions, several colors, and a few random basic phrases. Oh well.

As for interesting stuff in my life though, I got a cat. He's named Ranma. Yes, that's after the anime/manga by the way since he was called Becky by the humane society here and marked as an unspayed female. So, of course, in complying with my apartment's regulations, when I went to get him spayed I was informed that he was in fact a neutered male. Fun times. Besides that though, all he does is eat, sleep, shed, look out the window, and is only willing to play for 5 minutes before getting bored. Basically, he's just like me except with a tail, one more leg, and more free time to do his sleeping. It makes me jealous. Fortunately for him (but regrettably for me though) his only real competition for my affection right now is a bamboo plant which I regularly forget to water yet still seems in fine health. I guess I'm just a master (albeit lazy) gardener that way.

More information to come if I successfully pass boards this time around

Four day weekend, yay! Spending more than half of it studying for spinal anatomy, not as yay!

Yeah... really not much else to say though. Basically my life is classes, studying (for pretty much the first time in my life), eating, sleeping, and occasionally reading for awhile at night or watching South Park and Futurama. The most social activity I get involved with is shopping for groceries unless you count talking to peoples for the five minutes between classes. I did manage to make it to my first Reel Big Fish concert awhile back though. It was pretty awesome. Back to studying for now though. C1 - L4 need to be known for my Thursday exam. Fun times...
Lab practicals suck almost as much as the painstaking process of studying for them. That is all

Time [insert adjective here] spent between classes:

I was going to write you a poem today
But then I remembered I can't write
I was going to sing you a song instead
But then I remembered I can't sing
I was instead going to just play music for you
But then I remembered I'm tone deaf
I hope you don't mind that I can't let you know in a more beautiful way
...But I love you


Also,


I was watching the clouds go by the other day
Looking for hearts and stars and animals
When I found one that didn't look to me like anything
I tried so hard to come up with something it reminded me of
I wanted so much for that cloud to be something else
And I almost convinced myself that it was
But I just couldn't see it...
I guess that really
Sometimes clouds
Just look like clouds


And one more


It's almost time now where I'll have to say goodbye
And I know I shouldn't hold any regrets
But it still saddens me to know
That we never did get to dance among the stars
However, at the time, our silent waltz in your basement was
For me, at least
Worth far more than any imperial ball

The End
I just found out that American Media recently decided to suspend publication of the world's only reliable news source. We're all doomed

Although not many things can ruin your sleep more than it either, there aren't many things that can make you feel more loved than a call at 2:30 in the morning by somebody to let you know they're thinking of you. Even if I'm still not fully comfortable talking to the person.

I wonder if anybody here even remembers my little book of quotes... anyway, here's a few good ones from some of my teachers:

"'Diameter of a neuron's perikaryon' how could you go another weekend without knowing that?"
"It gets more interesting the more bad things you have"
"Alcohol is a wonderful preservative for both the dead and the living"
"My wife nudges me and says, 'how long do you think those [giraffe] neurons are?' These are the kinds of conversations we have"
"Well, I'm gonna look that over later because I'm gonna try to find that you're not right"
--All from Prof. Lewellen, CNS instructor

"Dead people get me excited" --Overheard in gross anatomy lab

"So if a third metatarsal washes up on the beach you can find out how tall that person was"
"A library day is walk by the library and go 'oh, there's the library!"
--Both from Dr. Bhatti, Embryology instructor

"He's dead, he can't do anything to us" (referring to Aristotle)
"We're not ready yet to deliver the baby because we're out of time"
--Both from Dr. Faruqui, Neurophysiology instructor
I find that it's difficult to cook with a stove that can't get water to a rolling boil, an oven that doesn't work, and no microwave... Yay for turkey sandwiches

I just can't understand it anymore
I don't understand how the flowers can still bloom
Or how the wind can still blow
Or how the stream can still flow
I don't understand how the birds can still sing
Or how the grass can still grow
Or how the kids can still play
I don't understand how the earth can still spin
Or how the sun can still shine
Or how my heart can still beat
Without you...
The only thing I can still understand
Is why the clouds cry

So I almost forgot even how to make a new post and I'm sure right now several people are wondering something like, "Wait. Who's this person now and how did they get onto my friends page?"

Anyway, now that I'm at Palmer Chiropractic College and have a legitimate excuse to not post, I decided that maybe I'll start posting again on occasion. Often I think I'll avoid posts about myself and life though since I doubt I'll be up to much besides classes, labs, and even ::gasp!:: studying. I know, studying isn't something that I do or even really know how to, but today I actually studied up on some CNS class terms and what's more I think I did so successfully. Instead I'll probably end up doing the occasional poem, short fictional story, or random quiz I get off of somebody else's journal.

Ummm... That is all

Last entry and then I'm going to pack up the computer as well. Anyway, just so I don't have to make another post later, I might be coming back right after classes on the Friday before Labor day and will head back for Vermillion later on Monday. However, I'll be in NoDak most of the time actually so I probably won't be able to do anything except on Monday and that's only assuming anybody would want to.

In other news, I finally got less than 50 (a 49, so not by much) at Kuehn Golf Course (par of 30... <.<   >.> ) and I only had to bend the rules a little bit to do so. lol

Every pirate lives for something different. For some, it's the open sea. For others (the masochists), it's the food. For you, it's definitely the fighting. Like the rock flint, you're hard and sharp. But, also like flint, you're easily chipped, and sparky. Arr!

Due to a sudden change of heart in many things, I have decided that, despite the vote, the livejournal will not remain active even at the same uneventful level as now. Also, I won't have anybody think I planned this before the vote, because I didn't. Instead things happened that made me rethink and reconsider a bit.

However, it shall remain for a limited number of purposes
1. It shall herald any significant returns to Sioux Falls
2. It shall announce the death of Branden (if such a tragedy should occur) just as I would expect his to announce mine
3. It'll still be used for me to look at everybody else's friends only posts (if I'm marked as a friend), so please don't remove me from any such lists unless you really want to.
4. Going along with (3), it shall also be used to post comments (not that I do often anyway)
5. In case I decide to use it again, not only shall I announce it here, I'll also have it ready

Basically, I don't see why it would matter a whole lot anyway since, as room mates, Branden's livejournal should be sufficient to tell all the interesting stories anyway and all you'll really miss out on is how my own classes are going which I don't really post about anyway

In other news, I converted a bunch of loose change into bills recently. When handing them over, I said jokingly that I'll probably end with exactly 99 cents left over (after a dollar amount anyway). It gets worse than that though. Not only did I get 99 cents after that right on, the only reason was because the machine wouldn't accept a single dented nickle I had...

Think I finally got my final schedule done. 17 credits total

Psychology MWF 8am - 8:50am
Composition 2 MWF 9am - 9:50am
Elementary Latin MTWTH 10am - 10:50am
Cellular and molecular biology MWF 11am - 11:50am
Fundementals of speech MWF 12pm - 12:50pm
Cellular and molecular biology lab W 6pm - 8:50pm

Hate English classes though (comp. II and speech is also included), but I decided for those two more cedits (total) over an advanced chem. class that meets a requirement (both those aforementioned classes are also required). Thankfully, I'm fairly good at bio, so hopefully that'll be fine. As for elementary Latin, it's 101. The 201 and 202 classes are recommended for those who have already had one or two years of high school Latin and considering I ranked among top in the nation both years of high school Latin in national exams, 101 should be slothfully easy. Psychology I've noticed that with only a little bit of any studying, I probably could have gotten out of it anyway. Basically, that lets you know when to call me or when I'll be online since my livejournal may die (except to announce whenever I return to town). Hopefully I'll get a job though and that schedule will be more cluttered. lol

In other news, I completely neglected to take the will of the people into account in my decision to kill off my livejournal. Therefore, I call a vote. Anybody who doesn't vote (based on those who I expect possibly read this at all) automatically count as votes to kill it off (so basically if you want it dead, you don't even have to say anything and thus time is saved. Yay, right?) Vote ends Friday night, of course.

Nonsensical posting replaced by a quize since I haven't put one up in awhile
Your element is Light. Your heart is pure and
shining with love. You believe in the goodness
of those around you and give almost everyone a
smile. You are not the kind to hide your
happiness and tend to smile all day long, both
in and out. But when sadness hits you, you
become very devastated and may be upset for
quite some time. What you need in your life is
friends, friends who will love you
unconditionally, like you love them. But you
have a naive nature and don't always notice
when someone is trying to hurt you. Some would
say you are oblivious to mean people, which
makes you an easy target. However, your true
friends will probably be there for you and save
you. In school you are either the popular one
or the little weird one. It all depends if
"the higher people" find your caring
side irritating or not. Nevertheless, you have
a bubbly personality and are social. Big partys
may not be your thing since you want bonding
time with your friends, so slumber-partys fit
you more. You like the happy things in life and
like everyone else to be as happy as you are.
Rate and message!

I have decided quite recently to no longer say "gasp!" in place of an actual gasp. Instead there shall be no gasping involved and it shall be replaced by "egads!" I know this is a sudden decision and one that some people may not be willing to accept, but I'm hoping this will not mean the end of your world. After all, it's not so far as me actually shaving off my soul patch which allegedly some people would kill me if I were to do so. In this time of sorrow at the passing of my saying "gasp!" I feel it is only right to begin with a brief story of its life. It all began when I decided my gasps suck and that I'm better at just saying it and it all ended today when I decided "egads!" is all good too. The End. The gasp is dead, long live egads!

In all honesty, I'm not sure how long I can go without my gasp, but I'll try.

I have suddenly realized a horrible problem that Branden and I face before heading off to college and that is that neither of us has yet mentioned anything about a can opener. The obvious solution is to simply not have any canned foods. Because meal plans are mandatory, we could just go along with that, but it is far less fun than coming up with our own edibles (that's my opinion, at least). However, we must wonder as to if we can actually survive without the precious canned foods. As some of you may know, the price of canned foods is dropping worldwide as more ranches are opening up to raise them as they graze about in their large herds and newer techniques ensure better health and thus higher volume for each can. I think it goes without saying that cheap food = good for college students. Oh to lead the simple life of the canned food and have little worries in the world, but alas, as the natural predator I am left forced to hunt and kill and eat them instead, but we seem to be lacking in the tools necesarry to open their thick hides: Freakishly sharp teeth and/or can openers. I fear we may starve...







Or have to buy a can opener

I would like to take this time to say a few words about the Fryn' Pan on 10th street. Actually, I don't even think it should be called Fryn' Pan. I'ma call it Tom's. Tom's not only charges more for a relatively sub-par BFR, it also serves it with butter tabs instead of tubs, and I think we all know how of a differance that one letter can make when it comes to butter. They even lacked any pitchers of water and instead gave us bigger glasses and refills is all. Were it not for my younger brother almost deliberatly making it harder on them at the register, Branden and I would have been even more disappointed. Perhaps worst of all was that, despite how crowded it was, we did not notice a single stoner table. It completely lacked all the atmosphere that I have grown to love in Fryn' Pan. In summation, Tom's makes me sad and want to eat at the Fryn' Pan instead.

Also, no offense to Erica for working there. Instead I feel sorry for her... Poor Erica! ::hugs::

This concludes part two of my nonsensical posting

So I was eating some chocolate with almonds in there yesterday when I thought, "You know what some great nuts are? Brazil nuts... and macadamia..." And then I also thought, "Why don't people eat more brazil nuts? Are we a culture that's racist against the nuts of Brazil?" I, myself, love Brazil nuts and macadamia nuts, but does that alone make me biased against other nuts? Should we even distinguish between other nuts? After all, I don't like walnuts as much as other nuts and even if they were all just called nuts, I'd still notice that walnuts look and taste just a bit differant. Sure I don't mind walnuts and I'll eat them in brownies and stuff (especially Collison's special brownies), but I'm not going to go out of my way to eat them, and why should I? I suppose in the end some people just don't like Brazil nuts and some people don't like walnuts. I should just relish in the fact that it leaves more Brazil nuts for me. Would somebody mind buying me some Brazil and/or macadamia nuts? I really want some now...

Yep. I'm pretty sure that my room is haunted or that, at the very least, one of my graduation balloons is. And yes, in case some of you didn't know, I am at least a little superstitious. Anyway, the balloon was positioned at the opposite corner of the room as me (and since I have the largest room in the house even compared to that of my parents, that's no small distance) and then about a minute after I woke up it just kind of hovered over to above my chair (to my left) and floated there for about 5 seconds that floated to just over my desk (almost immediatly to my left). There it sat for about another 5 seconds and then kind of lowered and continued moving closer to me until it shifted to moving in front of my fan. When it got there, it just lunged at me! That it did so wasn't surprising, of course, because the fan was on, but the way it moved to get there was kind of creepy. After that though it just kind of flew around in circles above me rising when moving away from me and falling whenever it came near my face until it floated along my bookshelf at the head of my bed (I moved out of the way a bit not wanting to disturb the balloon) it made one more circle and then rested on the pillow next to mine for a bit before checking out the books above the head of my bed where it got its tail stuck between the wall and a book. It got out, did some more circles, and then got stuck again later where it now remains.

Yeah... it was problably a lot more creepy/entertaining if you actually saw it.

I have decided what friends I shall try and look for specifically when I make it to USD. Although I shall be accepting of anybody willing to be friendly towards me, I think it would be especially great to find people who really don't get stressed out over much of anything. Whether they are total slackers or taking the upper difficulty classes, just so long as they know that things will work out in the end either way, it's all good. It would be especially beneficial if I could find such people who are also not potheads but instead just act like they might as well be (i.e. randomness without drugness). Kind of like Mark, maybe. Speaking of which, Mark shall be there apparently, so that's one right there. Yay. So although anybody would be all good (because peoples are generally cool), that would be for the best. And if they aren't, I may wind up dragging them with me into little states of complete relaxation and bliss of their own.
